name: Alice Hargrave
description: Artist: Alice Hargrave Title: Untitled (family pictures) ; blue skies # 10 Size: 8.5x11 Paper: Hahnemuhle photo rag 308 Edition: 12 Price: $100 SIGNED! From the artist: "Sometimes, a gaze to the sky stops you in your tracks and you cannot do anything but soak in the performance, the stage set, the actors floating by … it is there and then before you know it, it is gone." what we are not seeing is there lingering like dust in the air a scent a breeze a distant laugh Sandra Binion , 2010

name: Matthew Crowther
description:
Artist: Matthew Crowther
Title: Ohio
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: Moab Lasal Exhibition Luster
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED

From the artist:
“I am most interested in telling stories through suggestion and atmosphere, rather than actually depicting an event or series of events. I like to leave the details open ended, so the viewer can fill in the gaps for themselves, and find something new each time they come back to the image. With this photograph of a deer blind in southeastern Ohio in mid-summer, I have numerous stories that fit this place, in this light; stories that feel right being set here. Some of them are mine, some belong to friends, and some I’ve made up. That is what keeps me coming back to this image, and what I hope other viewers find in it as well."

name: Sarah Malakoff
description:
Artist: Sarah Malakoff
Title: Untitled Interior (B in white room)
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: Epson Ultra Premium Luster
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED!

From the artist:
"The photographs in Second Nature are a collection of private spaces that ask the viewer to imagine the people who inhabit them.  In images like Untitled Interior (B in white room), I’m interested the duality between the wild and the domesticated.  Pets have a unique status as both animals with primal instincts and as esteemed family members and creatures of comfort. There exists an uncanny and often humorous interplay between the decorative choices we make and our animal residents.  Here the overwhelmingly white interior matches the cat, and it is unclear whether this is an intentional or subconscious choice."

name: Roger Generazzo
description:
Artist: Roger Generazzo
Title: At the End of Gowanus Canal, Brooklyn, NY, 2009
Size: 8.5x11
Paper: Hahnemuhle Fine Art Pearl
Edition: 12
Price: $100

SIGNED

From the artist:
When the Dutch settled this eastern part of Brooklyn in the 17th Century, the Gowanus Creek spread out like fingers into navigable streams filled with natural marshes and marine life. During the 1860s the creek was dredged and converted into a long canal to facilitate commerce that built up along it. Unfortunately, many businesses dumped its waste and the city its sewage into the canal, creating over years a well-known polluted and odorous waterway. In fact, it still is, but now it's on the EPA’s Superfund Priorities List to be rehabilitated.

name: Sarah Moore
description:
Artist: Sarah Moore
Title: Self-portrait in the Midst of a Bad Week 
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: Epson Hot Press Natural
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED

About this photograph:
"I made this photograph during one of those bad weeks that seem to represent everything going wrong in your life.  I was extremely frustrated with my job, I was losing faith in photography, and my heart felt broken.  Those small things passed, as they usually do, but at the time I felt trapped in New Mexico and trapped within myself.  I wanted to make an upfront photograph that truly showed myself during this confusing time.  Yet, thanks to the wind, even I was to remain hidden behind New Mexico's impulsive gusts."

name: Matthew Conboy
description:
Artist: Matthew Conboy
Title: WSW, 1880 (Boone County, KY)
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: Epson Ultra Premium Luster
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED

"This image is from the 1880 center of population and is located on a closed down section of the parking lot at Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport.  Although the airport is only miles from downtown Cincinnati, the atmosphere at this center was as quiet as could be with no planes taking off or landing on the runway that was just on the other side of this fence.  I am standing looking westward toward the 1890 center that lays 47 miles away in Decatur County, IN."

name: Luke Strosnider
description:
Artist: Luke Strosnider
Title: Untitled (Blue Coat from the series "I Wish You Where Here")
Size: 8.5x11
Paper: Hahnemuhle Photo Rag Pearl
Edition: 12
Price: $100

SIGNED

"Despite the chill of Paris in November, my wife and I decided to get
sorbet. As we resumed our strolling along the Seine, this radiant blue
cut through the grey. It was a visual connection, but because I was
just passing through, I'd never really know this person or the story
of their coat. My series "I Wish You Where Here" explores these
feelings of connections made and missed as I lived briefly in Europe,
somewhere between a resident and a tourist."

name: Tammy Mercure

Artist: Tammy Mercure

performs with his horse Lucky Joe all over the country. In 2007, he

name: Alan Hunter
description:
Artist: Alan Hunter
Title: Untitled (Hummingbird)
Size: 8.5x11
Paper: Hahnemuhle Photo Rag
Edition: 12
Price: $100

SIGNED

From the Artist:
"Hummingbird is an image from Beneath a Greying Sky, a project influenced by the burgeoning underground black metal music scene in the Pacific Northwest. Like the music that inspired it, this image juxtaposes the quiet beauty of our natural world and certain darker, destructive forces both in and outside our control."

name: Cheryle St. Onge
description:
Artist: Cheryle St. Onge 
Title: Untitled (Moth)
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: Hahnemuehle Fine Art  
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED

From the artist:
"This moth survived a storm on the island of Man-O - War in the Bahamas. Whether it is predictors, weather, mankind - no matter life unfolds. The ravaged beauty is palpable, so battered and of course this happens around all of us,  everyday, all the time. "

name: Polly Chandler
description:
Artist: Polly Chandler
Title: "And the Sea turns into a Mirror" 
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: Epson Velvet
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED

From the Artist: 
"This image, "And The Sea Turns Into A Mirror", comes from my latest project which is a series of narratives based on my personal interpretations of the music and lyrics by the singer-song writer, Tom Waits.  The song that inspired this particular image is titled "Fish And Bird", a simple ditty about a bird and whale that fall in love, and obviously, cannot be together."

name: Noelle McCleaf
description: Artist: Noelle McCleaf Title: "Under the Tangerine Tree" Size: 8.5x11 Paper: Hahnemuehle Photo Rag Baryta Edition: 12 Price: $100 SIGNED From the Artist: Under the Tangerine Tree is a self-portrait from the series A Bee in Her Bonnet. Most of the body of work from this series is photographed on a large plot of land out Route 70 in the heart of South Florida. Fruit trees are a large part of the Floridian landscape. This image was taken in early summer when the humidity begins to rise, so the tangerines and oranges are just past their prime. This tree goes unpicked, so the rotting peels fall back to the earth. The character in this image is a sexualized not-so-southern belle, and she confronts the gaze of the viewer on her own volition. She cautiously invites the viewer into the landscape, surrounded by strange objects stored on an old patio.

name: Rob Walters
description: Artist: Rob Walters Title: "6th and Canal St, Missouri Valley, IA" Size: 8.5x11 Paper: Hahnemuehle Fine Art Edition: 12 Price: $100 SIGNED From the Artist: This photo is from a project called Aksarben. The word comes from spelling Nebraska backwards meant to represent "turning Nebraska around". Coined as a positive spin on development and growth in the heartland, I have always found it a nice play on ideas and expectations that may pop in your head when thinking of the midwest. The project began with some long drives exploring Omaha and it's surrounding area. As the region has lost much of it's identity with the homogeneous nature of development that is sweeping the landscape, I wanted to explore the things that remain and hint to what had come before and still seems to find it's way to the surface. 6th and Canal St, Missouri Valley, IA was taken about 20 miles outside of the city and illustrates the stark contrast between the Omaha Metro and the surrounding rural communities.

name: Rainer Hosch
description:
Artist: Rainer Hosch
Title: NYC 03.08.11 - 04:23:39 PM
Size:  8.5x11
Paper: Hahnemuehle Fine Art Pearl
Edition: 12
Price: $100

SIGNED

From the Artist:

"From the New York New York Series, this image was taken in front of the Luis Vuitton store on the corner of 57th street and 5th Avenue in 2011. I was walking up 57th Street towards the corner when I spotted the lady standing in front of the shop's window with her bag and started shooting while walking. People came in and out of frame constantly and I actually stopped and waited to get this frame of just her, without her noticing me. The whole process took about 30 seconds and the eight and last frame of the sequence was the one that I was looking for before I moved back into the flow of the city. If you look closely you will see my reflection in the window, so it is also a self portrait of me at work."

name: Keren Moscovitch
description:
Artist: Keren Moscovitch
Title: Fingers and Waist
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: Canson Barryta
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED

From Issue 51

"Me Into You is a photographic series that explores love, intimacy and sexuality as contextualized within my experiences in an open relationship. By photographing myself and my partner with our lovers, I explore the rich emotional terrain between love and hate, attraction and fear, curiosity and disappointment. 

Fingers and Waist is about touch, warmth and eroticism. It investigates the way that a lover’s body feels, the desire to reach out of our own skin and make contact. It also explores the availability – or lack thereof – of another person’s body and looking at oneself in relationship to another."

name: Rachel Cox
description:
Artist: Rachel Cox
Title:  Don't Smile, Smile
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: Epson Exhibition Fiber
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED

From Issue 50

"Don't Smile, Smile is an image from my most recent body of work SHINY GHOST, a photographic series dealing with the fading character of my Grandmother due to a degenerative brain disease that quickly claimed her life. The image deals with ideas surrounding identity within pictures, specifically, the ubiquitous studio portrait most of us possess in some form. The two pictures in the image speak towards truth and artifice, beauty and age, life and death. The photograph simultaneously epitomizes her glamour while also freezing it in two distinct representations, reminding us of our own mortality. "

name: Rachael Short
description:
Artist: Rachael Short
Title:  Eclipse Light, 2012
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: hahnemuehle fine art
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED

From Issue 50

"Eclipse Light" was photographed in 2012 during the solar eclipse. It was photographed with my iPhone which is now my primary camera after a car accident that left me a quadriplegic in 2010. The iPhone didn't capture the typical eclipse image you would expect to see but the light that afternoon was so eerie and I feel I captured that in this image. I photograph with the iPhone daily capturing anything and everything I can.  Mostly inspired by nature, people, and places. "

name: Rachel Wolfe
description:
Artist: Rachel Wolfe
Title:  Park
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: Epson Ultra Premium Matte Paper
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED 

From Issue 50

"Park" was photographed in 2010 on Kodak 160NC film through a Hasselblad 501C, as part of the ESPLA project and is included in the publication by the same title. The works included in ESPLA (Especially L.A.) investigate ideas of existence, place and finding the self within the contemporary landscapes of Los Angeles.The landscapes investigates stories of Eastern culture enmeshed with the West Coast lifestyle. This image was photographed in a Costco parking lot at sunset. The juxtaposition of soft shadow of a manicured tree near the stark shopping cart in a vacant area, captured the essence of the social events taking place just behind me. The transience of the situation is highlighted in the depiction of this "Park."

name: Bryon Darby
description:
Artist:  D. Bryon Darby	
Title:  "Seventy Flights in Ninety Minutes, Phoenix"
Size: 5.5 x 9.5 on 8.5x11 paper
Paper: Museo Portfolio Rag
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED

From Issue 50

From the artist
"For three years, my family and I lived directly within the flight path of Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport. Located in the heart of the city, Sky Harbor is the ninth-busiest airport in the United States. On any given day, some 1,200 aircraft fly through the airspace above the Phoenix suburbs.  The ever-present roar of 737, much like the late-summer lull of suburban lawn mowers.

Seventy Flights in Ninety Minutes was made from the top of Hayden Butte in Tempe, Arizona. The publicly accessible volcanic butte is just beyond the airport and is straddled by Sky Harbor’s two busiest flight paths. For 90 minutes, I photographed every airplane that flew overhead, and then I digitally stitched together the many individual photographs. I hoped to re-create the experience of living in a flight path by compressing an hour and a half into one apparently single moment."

** all prints ordered after June 1st with ship on July 15

name: Jon Horvath
description:
Artist: Jon Horvath
Title:  My Grandmother’s First Tattoo (80 Years Old)
Size: 8.5x11 
Paper: Epson Exhibition Fiber
Edition: 12 
Price: $100

SIGNED

From Issue 50

From the artist:
"This is my grandmother, Elly.  She is my father’s mother.  In my family, she is affectionately known as “Granny”, or at times “Granola”.  She spent most of her life doing secretarial work, has a high bowling score in the 250’s, and dresses monochromatically.  As a teenager, she would often pull up pieces of freshly laid tar and chew it like gum.  As a child, I used to slide plastic spoons into her fluffy white hair.  She never let on knowing.  On the occasion of her 80th birthday, she got her first tattoo, the butterfly pictured here.  Since that time she has added a full bouquet of roses to her right forearm.  Granny never finishes her dessert."

name: Polly Braden
description: Artist: Polly Braden Title: One New Change, 2012 Size: 8.5x11 Paper: C-Type Edition: 12 Price: $100 SIGNED From Issue 48 From the series London's Square Mile: London's financial centre, known as 'London's Square Mile', covers one square mile of land. The photographs have charted the rise and more recently fall of the City. Whilst the City branded itself and was seen from the outside as a slick, modern and confident place in 2006 these days it is just as often the place protestors choose to put up tents or the starting place for the public sector march. Read more about Polly and this photograph here This photograph ships from the UK

name: Richard Bram
description: Artist: Richard Bram Title: Sno-Cone, SoHo, New York 2011 Size: 8.5x11 Paper: Canson-Infinity Rag Photographique, 210 gsm. Edition: 12 Price: $100 SIGNED From Issue 48 "In March 2011, one of my favorite places to shoot is the intersection of Broadway and Spring Street in SoHo. On a busy Saturday, it is absolutely heaving with people, constantly changing and offering up new possibilities every second. Trying to make visual sense of it can be overwhelming if you're not prepared for that torrent of faces. "Sno-Cone" was shot very close to the subjects, no more than three or four feet, with a 24mm lens. While the eye is drawn immediately to the girl and her bright red Sno-Cone, the picture also is about the dance of color across the frame, the implied 'X' of the converging diagonals and the joy of sunlight on a breezy, crisp early Spring day." Read more about Richard and this photograph here

name: Stella Kalaw
description: Artist: Stella Kalaw Title: Man on escalator. Market Street. San Francisco, CA Size: 8.5x11 Paper: Fuji Crystal Archive paper Edition: 12 Price: $100 SIGNED From Issue 48 "This picture was taken during the afternoon commute in downtown San Francisco. The escalator banks took people down to the BART trains going to the East Bay. On this particular day, I had time to hang around and look for interesting pictures before catching the train home. I first noticed the pedestrians walking along the street so I framed my viewfinder to capture the flow. It was one of those serendipitous moments when the gentleman stepped on the escalator just as I clicked the shutter. I only discovered through the playback that he looked directly at the camera at the right moment." Read more about Stella and this photograph here

name: Deanne Andrus - Helsinki-Atlanta
description: Artist: Deanne Andrus Title: Helsinki Atlanta Size: 8.5x11 Paper: Ilford Gold Fibre Silk Edition: 12 Price: $100 SIGNED From Issue 47 about this image, in her words. . . "My husband sends me pictures as a way of communicating while he is away for work. In the past he spent a lot of time in Finland. This picture was taken by the Harbor in Helsinki. To symbolize unity and connection to each other, I projected this Finnish image onto our fireplace mantel at home. For the final image I experimented both with and without the fireplace turned on. By including the fire in the image it made the image more alive, much warmer and seemed to blend the two spaces into one." Read more about Deanne and this photograph here

name: Gwynne Johnson - Untitled (Hand in Grass)
description: Artist: Gwynne Johnson Title: Untitled Size: 8.5x11 Paper: Ilford Luster Edition: 12 Price: $100 SIGNED From Issue 47 About this image, in her words. . . "This photograph was made for a body of work dealing with the experience of the emigrant. While making these images I was thinking about those who are geographically and temporally exiled, by choice or force, and the resulting feelings of separation and estrangement that often accompany such circumstances. The emigrant straddles two places and cultures, the old and the new, and often must live in the in between. The gash in the earth functions in a number of ways: it refers to a physical separation of land, a psychological wound, and an interruption in continuity. The hand similarly offers multiple reads but ultimately its intentions and desires remain ambiguous. Does it look forward, seeking to wrap a finger under the earth to peal back the sod and reveal a future? Or does it reach longingly into the darkness in the hope of touching the past?" Read more about Gwynne and this photograph here

name: Galina Kurlat - Amanda IIIX
description: Artist: Galina Kurlat Title: Amanda IIIX Size: 8.5x11 Print Type: Archival Pigment Print Printer Type: Epson R2400 Printer Ink Type: Epson Paper: Epson Premium Luster Edition: 12 Price: $100 SIGNED From Issue 47 "The photographs in this series are made using Type 55 Polaroid positive/negative film, a film which was expired in 2008. As I peeled apart the film for this image a feeling of despair and panic came over me. Knowing that I have a limited amount of film to work with, the grey corners were all too familiar signs that the image had not processed properly. The photograph slowly revealed itself to be a perfect balance of medium and subject. Amanda's choice to turn away from the camera is reinforced by the veil like peeling of the film. I specifically work with expired Polaroid film to allow an aspect of serendipity and chaos into my work. " Read more about Galina and this photograph here
